    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Cleveland</placeName>
                <date>May 6<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1857. 5617</date>
            </p>
            <p>Rev &amp; Dear Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">I am duly in receipt of<lb/> your esteemed favor bearing date of the
                    <date>3d</date><lb/> inst this morning and regret that I am<lb/> in possession
                of the desired information<lb/> that might otherwise delay an immediate<lb/> answer.
                Our mutually valued friend <persName>Alfred<lb/> T. Jones Esq.</persName> wrote us a
                very eloquent letter some<lb/> time since in reference to the subject you have<lb/>
                ably advocated and the trial we then made<lb/> to obtain loans from our
                co-religionist re-<lb/>-sulted only in upraidings and derision.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Not I assure you without just cause. The<lb/> congregation to which
                we belong is in debt<lb/> to the amount of $2000. for building &amp; balance<lb/> of
                money due on lot It consists of only 20<lb/> members upon whom from the
                beginning<lb/> all the responsibility and liability has<lb/> devolved. We have been
                but recently threat<lb/>-ened with a suit of ejectment which<lb/> caused us all to
                bleed to our uttermost pe<lb/>-cuniarily the poorest among us advancing<lb/> a $100.
                but we still have the heavy<lb/> burden of $2000 hanging o'er our necks<lb/> and
                weighing us down with more</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>or less anxiety. Under these circumstances the idea<lb/> of contributing to the aid
                of others is almost scow-<lb/>-led at, however charity-like. But this arises
                from<lb/> a two-fold reason, first <hi rend="underline">our own burdens</hi>,
                secondly<lb/> the remembrance of the treatment we received<lb/> when we made an
                appeal to our brethren<lb/> in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> and
                    <placeName>N.Y.</placeName> where our mission-<lb/>ary or rather messenger after
                spending a<lb/> whole month succeeded in raising only the<lb/> paltry sum of $160.
                Think of the mighty cities<lb/> of <placeName>N. Y.</placeName> &amp;
                    <placeName>Phila</placeName> combinedly giving only $160!<lb/> A private
                donation would have amounted to<lb/> more if actuated by the proper spirit and<lb/>
                ability! No, my dear Sir I regret to say<lb/> there is not the slightest prospect of
                raising<lb/> a dollar in aid of the laudable object you<lb/> warmly advocate, it
                would be a great source<lb/> of happiness to me to be the means in however<lb/>
                slight a manner to assist our co-religionists<lb/> in <placeName>Phila</placeName>
                to place you at the head of a prosperous congre-<lb/>gation, but lacking the
                necessary power I must<lb/> be placed among those of your friends who<lb/> have all
                the will but none of the ability.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your return to the ministry will be<lb/> warmly hailed by your
                brethren throughout<lb/> the Union and considered by all your true<lb/> friends as
                an eventual triumph. How grati</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>-fying<lb/> it must be to you after so many long years to<lb/> once more and that to
                in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> assume<lb/> the exalted office it has been
                your destiny to<lb/> so ably fill, permit me to congratulate you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I cannot express to you the real plea-<lb/>sure—the very <hi
                    rend="underline">thought</hi> of your return affords<lb/> to my heart, believe
                me I hail it with no<lb/> ordinary emotions of pride and gratification<lb/> of
                course at present perhaps forever the “Advo-<lb/>-cate” will be abandoned—your
                ministerial<lb/> duties and your editorial not permitting ad<lb/>-ditional—at least
                at present, perhaps it is<lb/> as well, the generation to come will be a more<lb/>
                intelligent one. I mean of our people in this<lb/> country, and they will require a
                literature<lb/> of their own. I shall forthwith consti-<lb/>tute myself your active
                agent here for your<lb/> admirable journal the occident and as<lb/> meet “our
                people” weekly now at the lodge,<lb/> being a member of the I.O.BB. I shall
                have<lb/> opportunities which shall not be lost. I<lb/> begin by sending you the
                name of<lb/>
                <persName>D. Cauffman</persName> to whom from <date>1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> of
                    May</date><lb/> you may send the Occident <del>for one year</del><lb/> I shall
                exert myself in your further<lb/> behalf in this respect on every occasion<lb/> and
                the pleasure of this aiding to</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>disseminate the doctrines promulgated <del>in you</del><lb/> through your journal,
                will be “sweet recompense<lb/> for all my labors.” It may be that I may<lb/> in some
                of my “inspired moments” send<lb/> you a fledgling for the grave columns of<lb/> the
                Occident but it will much depend<lb/> upon “time” and the “will” to do anything<lb/>
                that smacks of literary recreation or labor.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your friends here who esteem you so warm<lb/>-ly beg me to assure
                you of the gratification<lb/> your return to the pulpit will afford<lb/> them. Both
                    <persName>Mr &amp; Mrs Davis</persName> desire (with<lb/> my Brother &amp;
                    <add>?</add>) to be kindly<lb/> remembered. Thank God our little ones<lb/> have
                come through the “fire &amp; water” of their<lb/> recent long &amp; painful not to
                say serious<lb/> sickness in safety the gloom that has<lb/> so long hung over our
                household is fast<lb/> disappearing under the blessed and<lb/> benigrant<add>?</add>
                rays of returning Health &amp; Sunshine<lb/> With renewed assurances of esteem
                and<lb/> regard believe me</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">Very truly &amp; warmly</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">your friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">
                <persName role="author">B F. Peixotto</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
